{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958032101/0208.xml":{"full_text":"Labor\u2019s Fight on Recession\nIs Carried to Eisenhower\nThe AFL-CIO climaxed its drive to cure the nation\u2019s\n\u201cdangerously sick\" economy with a direct plea to Pres.\nEisenhower \u201cfor action without further delay.\"\nThe federation\u2019s eight-man Executive Committee told\nthe President the statistical evidence of suffering and hard\nship is so everwhelming\nthat\nand\nit's\nun\n\"unnecessary\nwise\" to wait for next\nmonth's unemployment figures\nbefore taking action.\nMeany told reporters after\nthe meting that the AFI. (TO\nsending a memorandum\nwas\nto the President, on the basis\nof the committee\u2019s \u201cinformal\ndiscussion\u2019\nwith him.\nsup\nporting the conclusion that\nthings will he \u201cworse, rather\nthan better,'\nat the end of\nMarch.\nThe committee emphasized to\nthe President. Meany continued,\nthat the situation was \u201cfar more\ngrave, far more dangerous than\nthe American people believe.\"\nwould give\nThe\nmemorandum\ndetails of the economic indica\ntors showing that \"action now\nis demanded, he said\nThe committee's visit to the\nWhite House topped a three\nday emergency\nconference\nin\nWashington keyed to the theme\n\u201cPut America Back to Work\nAbout 1,000 delegates, rep\nresenting every section of the\ncountry, were briefed on the\neconomic and legislative situ\nation and moved onto Capitol\nHill to give their rongresss\nmen and senators a first hand\naccount of unemployment\nand\neconomic hardships in\ntheir areas.\nWhile the delegates spread\ntheir story on the Hill. Means\ngave the President a letter de\ntailing the AFL\nthe need for\nfor a tax cut\nviews on\nne action\nd federal\nu n e m plovment\nimmedia\nimprove.\ncompensation\nstandards, increased defense ex\npend itures.\na comprehensive\npublic works program.\nand\na\nnumber of other anti recession\nmeasures\nMeany Sounds Warndng\nMeany. in a hard-hitting key\nnote speech (see excerpts this\npage l earlier had warned the\nAUTO W\nAND FENDER\nREPAIR\n\"If it\u2019s any help this is what it used to look like\"\nG\nMiller\u2019s Pure Oil Service\nBERDAN at HAVERHILL\nGR. 5-7581\nKemp Jackson Gulf Service\nX\nDETROIT at OAKWOOD CH. 3-0684\nClem\u2019s Marathon Service\nDETROIT at PHILLIPS\nHerb\u2019s Gulf Service\nCOLLINGWOOD at ASHLAND\nGR. 2-0342\nCH. -0432\n(sobo\nRay Lentz Sohio Service\nFEARING at DUNHAM\nWA. 0173\nTOLEDO UNION\nJOURNAL\nTrading Post\nRates: 10 rents a line (5 words), minimum 2 tines. RO\ncents. Hail uith cash or bring in to Room 203, I\nthrop Street, CH. 1-9120, Extension 33.\nIT in\nh a neral\nDirectors\nDAY-EDWARDS MORTUARY\n741 W Central Ave\nCH 4-075)\nHOEFLINGER MORTUARY\n901 Platt st\nOX 1-6768\nFOTH MORTUARY\n3310 Jefferson Ava\nCH\n1-3241\nABELE FUNERAL HOME\n1910 Cherrv St\nCH 3-3161\nPARKS D EMMERT FUNERAL HOME\n3983 Monroe St\nGR 2-3119\nH\nH\nEIRKENKAMP FUNERAL\nHOMES\u20141003 Broadway\nCH\nTRILBY Ohio. GR 4-3773\n3-2183\nBROWN FUNERAL HOME\n19 Grand Ava\nCH 2-8423\nMiacellaneoua\nFOR SALE\nMcGuffeys Eclectic\nSpeller. Call Grand Rapid* 21137\nAnyone witnessing accident front of\nSports Arena about 3 p.m\n1957 Please call OX. 3-4240.\nDec 32.\nMODERN School Of Astrology\nclasses being formed WAf 9552.\nNew\nUsed Cars\nFOR SALE: Jeep Station Wagons\n4-wheel drive Call CH 2-0071\ndelegates not to be ''misled\u2019\u2019 by\nthe political soothsayers and\nspellbinders from either side.\n\u201cThe Democrats know they\ncan make political capital out\nof talking about the recession\nand doing little about it.\n\"The Republicans hope to\nprotect themselves by hiding\nthe fact, that during a Repub\nAdministration,\nlic a n\nthe\neconomy has become danger\nously sick.\u201d\nIn his letter to the President.\nMeany said that \"without ran\ncor or partisanship the ac\ntions proposed to date are not\nenough to meet the needs of the\nsituation\nOutlining the\nprogram, Means\nail rio\u2019s\nconcluded\nthat the need for action was\nso acute that \u201cwaiting for the\nnext monthly unemployment\nfigures would be. in our opin\nion, unnecessary and unwise.\u201d\nThe President had said previ\nously that he would wait for\nthe March figures before de\nciding on a tax cut and other\nmoves to stem the recession.\nReuther hairs Panel\nAFL-CIO Vice Pres\nWalter\nof the\nRent her.\nchairman\nP\nCommittee on Economic Policy,\nchairing a panel session of the\nconference involving three sen\nators and a congressman. de\nclared the recession \"will not\ncorrect itself\nHe urged a two pronged tax\ncut\u2014an\nincrease in the per\nsonal exrmption and author\nity for the government to in\ntitute, if necessary, a 90-day\nmoratormm on collection of\nwithholding taxes. He reiter\nated\nalso the\nnecessitv for\npassage of legislation to set\nfederal\nfor\nnew\njobless benefits.\nThe\nstandards\nA FL CIO\nconference\nopened a few hours before the\ngovernment announced that un\nemployment had reached a 16\nService\nTHE TIPTOP Room. First A Main\nParties,\nSt\nAvailable for Receptions\nMeetings. Cali CH 3-3700\u2014EL. 1739.\nUNCLE JOHN S Food Co catering to\nparties and banquets RA 6-1110\nGERBFR CABINET SHOP\u2014Specialist\nin kitchen remodelng CH 2-9337\nPAY water gas phone. light bills at\nLocal 12 dues window\nMail your Sales Tax Stamps to F\nReno 425 Winthrop St\nNEW YORK Life Insurance Co Rich\nard C Duttey Agent CH 8-6461\nHall For Rent\u2014 Kitchen facilities. 3015\nDetroit near Central CH 6 4806,\nCOTTON SHAG RUGS washed, dried\ndyed A re-rubberized 3-Hour service\non most rugs. Mriendly Laundrymat.\n3644 Upton Ave. GR\n4-6096\nFruit Trees Shrubbery trimmed-spray\ned. CH 3-1934.\nTeleviaion Seta\nTV SET Home appliances ail types\n1954 W Central Ave\nHardware Suppliea\nPAINTS 41) kinds. low prices Colon\nial Hardware. 1854 Central\nIt thert tomething you no longer need and would like\nto give away to help tome other union member? lu\u00bbt cull\nour \"Gitt Away Column,\u2019*\nCHerry 1-9126, Ext. 33.\n4\n\nyear high with 5 2 million idle\nand amid a series of moves in\nCongress for public works and\nother anti-recession proposals.\nPlaces Blame Jointly\nShortly after Harrison bang\ned the opening gavel, Meany\nplaced the blame for inaction to\ndate jointly\n8\nn the Administra\ntion and Congress. The Admin\nistration, he said, is to blame\nfor short-sightedness, \u201cfor its\nbasic lack of confidence in the\nAmerican people and because\nit has done too little until it s\nalmost too late.\nThe Congress. he added, did\nnot need to wait for Adminis\ntration leadership, \u201cit could_it\nshould\u2014have moved before\nthis.\"\nThe A f L c l o president\nwarned the delegates to main\ntain a\nsense of urgency and\nnot to be misled by optimistic\nprophecies that when the\nemployment figures\nported next month\nare\nuin\nre\nthings\nare going to be a lot better.\"\nOur troubles will not have\ndiminished unless unemploy\nment is down bv at least\n\u25a0\u2019mi linn _ _.\n200,000 by a month from to\nday,\" he declared.\nHe gave top .priority in the\nanti recession program to a tax\ncut that would\npump new\ninto the\npurchasing\nimmediately\npower\neconomy\u2014an increase\nin the personal exemption from\n$600 to $700, or higher if neces\nsary.\nrI V\nToledo Scale\nScribblings\nBy DICK SONCKANT\nThe monthly meeting will he\nheld next Tuesday, March 25,\n1958. Meeting place is parlor A\nLocal 12 Hall on Winthrop and\nAshland St There will be 15\nhams distributed for Easter The\ndoor prize will be $125. An edu\nnational movie will be shown to\nall those who are interested at\n7.30 pm. After the business\nhand is\nMarch 25,\nat\nover there will be free'\nrefreshments downstairs.\nLet's\nmake this the best attended\nmonthly meeting of 1958.\nbest\nThe following men will jour\nney to Chelsea. Mich Saturday\nnf.,, no\nMarch 22, to\nfourth\nparticipate in the\nannual Chelsea Singles\nBowling Tournament:\n\u2022left, Dan Bieniek,\nJerry Jablonski, S\nAndy Kaminski, Bill\nGale\nTed Sobb,\nStan Golba,\nBillheimer\nMel Mikol, and Jim Rygalski!\nAlso\naccompanying them will\n--*9 uinii will\nbe a couple of former Scale em\n\u201cdevm.. 11 1 _\nPloyecs. Dick\nLutz\nBeckstet. In their\nance in the\nfinished 2nd\nlast\nand John\nappear\ntourney, Rygalski\nand four others\nfinished high on the prize list.\nOn the sick list\nStacko of Dept\nis Cherrie\n591 who has\nbeen off for better than a month?\nSorry we missed\nand we hope\nwork soon.\nyou re\nyou, Cherrie,\nback\nto\nit is wondered\nthe oil house has\nwhy E.S. of\ning out\nnot been\npass\ncigars. Wedding bells\nAmerican Floor\nSweepings\nBy NORM WITHERELL\nThere seems to be consider\nable confusion on the proposed\nchange in the Seniority Clause\nin our contract. The Company\nturned down the orginal change,\nproposed by the Committee\nThey countered with a proposal\nwhich was turned down by the\nCommittee. After considerable\nnegotiating a second proposal\nwas submitted by the Committee\nas follows:\nIf work becomes slack in\nA\nclassification the Company may\ntransfer the employee with the\nleast seniority in that classifica\ntion to another classification, if\nwork is available. If there is no\nother work available he shall\nexercise his seniority in his de\npartment first. If there is no\nemployee with less seniority in\nhis department he shall then\nexercise his plantwide seniority,\ndisplacing the employee with\nthe least seniority in the classi\nfication into which he bumps\nFor example:\nIf work on the turret-lathes\nslack the Company\nbecomes\nmay transfer the 'youngest. in\nseniority employee in that clas\nsification to any other classify\ncation in the plant, where work\nis available, or if there is none\nhe shall bump the employee\nwith the least seniority in the\nex\nAmerican machine shop,\nchiding the sweeper and de\nclassifications first. If\ngreaser\ntheir is\nno\nemployee in the\nAmerican machine shop who has\nless seniority than he has, he can\nthen bump any employee in any\nlassification in any department\nin the plant, who has less senior\nity than he has. whose work he\nc\ncan perform.\nAs in the past, the Company\ncan\nstill transfer an employee\nto any other classification, where\nwork is available in which case\nthe employee transfered shall\nreceive his own rate of pay or\nthe rate of the job to which he\nis transfered if it is higher. This\npart of the clause has not been\nchanged.\nI hope this answers any ques\nturns you may have had and it\nis a little more clear now.\nI had to remind Ralph '\u2022ab\nsent-minded professor\u201d Jones\nthat he\nwon\nthe\nfive dollar\ndrawing at our\nlast meeting.\nHow forgetful can you get?\nFor you people who are al\nways looking for something for\nnothing at every Local 12\nmeting. held on the second Fri\nday of the month, the Friday. a\nweek following our Unit meet\ning. drawings are held. Merchan\ndise certificates, redeemable at\nthe Colonial Hardware Store, in\nthe amounts of $5.00, $7 50 and\nthe\n$12 50 are among the prizes..\nAnyone can win but, you must\nbe there\nrang Jan 1B for Elmer. Many\nhappy returns\nSarah Beasley of Dept 590\nhas also returned from sick\nleave. Its good to see you work\ning again, Sarah.\nI\nCondolences\nare\noffered to\nthe family of Lee Jordan whose\ngrandmother passed away, and\nto Ray Moore whose sister died,\nalso to A. L. McGee whose fa\nther passed away.\nFINEST in\nFIRMTERE\nHillebrand Brothers Co.\ni\nM3 NO. ST. CLAIR ST.\nCH. 1-5842 1\nBARON STEEL CO.\nToledo, Ohio\nWM. T. PHILLIPS CO.. Inc.\nToledo's Oldest Seed and Garden Supply House\n519 MONROE STREET\nCHerry 1-7083\nWYNN BROS\nINC.\nWHOLESALE GROCERS\n1511 Wayne Street\nWA. 3145\nBeutler Red White Store\nFor Quality Foods At Lowest Prices\n705 SOUTH STREET\nCHerry 6-0392\n207 KNAPP ST.\nPARK HOTEL RESTAURANT\nTrv Our Steaks, Chops and Fish Dinners\nI\n1\nCHerry 4-8552\n1702\nWayne St.\nROWE INDUSTRIES\nManufacturers of\nELECTRIC and ELECTRONIC DEVICES\n\n\nPIASECKI SERVICE STATION\nFRIEXDLY SERVICE\n5055 DORR STREET\nToledo, Ohio\n\n1 I\nJO. 1342\n2741 DETROIT AVE.\nSAVAGES MARKET\nQuality Crocerie\u00bb anti Uetilt\nCHerry 2-7804.\nHotel and Restaurant Supplies\nSTEGER-SHOWEL COMPANY\n206 SUMMIT STREET\nCH. 3-2112\n25 S. St. Clair St.\nCreeling* To Organised Labor\nALLEN FILTER CO.\nWATER COOLERS\n1\nt\nCH. 1-8711\nGreetings, AFL-CIO!\nDorr Street Hot Dog Chili Parlor\nOpen 24 Hours a Day\n1508 Dorr Street\nI.\n3\nChampion\nn\nV\nSparklets\nBy RALPH YOUNG\nUnion Office:\nSale* tax stamps this week\nfrom: Beulah Ruch, E 2nd; Bes\nsie Lens, L 2nd; Joe Sieja, EE\nChet Kaiser, committee\n1st;\nman; Del Sullivan, H Foreman;\nDonald Kaczala, H-Jan in A\n2nd; John S. Jakubowski, Stew\nard EE 3rd; Ronald Geer, Eng.\nToolroom.\nRolla Hatfield, retiree from\nDept. G, has been ill. We hope\nyou are feeling better, Rolla\nand the fellows in G send their\nbest wishes.\nShiver Marshall, C 1st, wishes\nto thank his friends for the\nflowers and gifts he received\nduring his recent illness.\nChessie Dye, plug tamping,\nsays thanks to everyone for the\ngifts, cards, and flowers she re\nceived during her sick leave.\nEvelyn (Katie) Pliska, Dept.\nL, wishes to thank everyone for\ntheir kindness during here rec\nent loss of her mother. Your\nsympathy was appreciated.\nLay-offs finally hit the\nChampion Spark Plug. Sorry\nto report that about 230 em\nployees are affected, the final\ncount has not been made yet.\nColonel Tarver, E 1st:\n\nBob Smith wishes to thank\neveryone for their thoughtful\nness and he appreciates the\nthree\nfrom\nS'\nFi\nage letter he received\n'red Hipp, last week.\nHerb Jennings sugests that as\nmany as possible send a post\ncard to Bob Smith soon.\nJoe Chaney celebrated h i s\nbirthday, March 13 by passing\nout slices of home-made cake to\nhis friends. His wife surprised\nhim with the gift of a beautiful\njacket. Happy birthday, Joe.\nRuth Burgbacker's new hair\ndo is becoming to her and in\nkeeping with the new trend\nwhich indicates that spring is\nhere.\nClyde Rauch's fresh hair cut\nharmonizes with the arrival of\nspring, March 21 and the pink\nsport shirt he wears makes him\nright in style\nLouise Nowicki celebrated her\n15th anniversary at Champion\non March 18\nGertrude Kuron returned to\nwork last week. She has a new\naddition to her family, a lovely\nlittle daughter, named Barbara\nAnn. Congratulations.\nMay King and Ted Siwa left\nfor the 3rd shift. Marcin Wall\nduda came on the 1st shift.\nMarcin is the husband of Lil\nlian.\nNews Flash! Hear Beatty,\nJohn Beiswenger, Larry Man\nkin and Dale McCracken have\ntaken out \u201cRight to Work\u201d\npetitions! Since they are on\nthe management side and\nmake the decisions lately as\nto whether you work or not,\nwhat need do they have for a\n\"Right to Work\u201d bill??? The\n230 employees being laid off\non March 28 have a right to\nwork and the Union agrees to\nit but Is the Company and\ntheir managers giving them\nthe right?\nThey probably will be cir\nP\nJ&L\nWare\nBy TED MODROWSKI\nMaybe\nyou\npeople who\nare\nunemployed and in some cases\nhave drawn your entire\namount\nof compensation can explain\nthis recent statement made by\nPresident Eisenhower:\n\"The\neconomy of this country is a lot\nstronger than the spirit of those\npeople that I see wailing about\nif\u201d\nit.\nIt is rather difficult to\nex\nplain when the cause of the\nwailing stems from lack of food\non the table and no money to\nclothe the family, but how\nwould Eisenhower know this\nwhen he has never been\nployed.\nunem\nIrv Rackowski tells the story\nof a very good friend of his\nwho never knew what real hap\npiness was until he got married.\nAnd then it was too late.\nLarry Knannlein topped this\nwith the tale of a buddy of his\nwho divorced his wife and then\nmarried her sister so he\nwouldn't have to break in a\nnew mother-in-law.\nErnie Luczak suggests that\nbefore you start figuring\nyour\nincome tax you practice on this\nproblem to sharpen\nartithmetic:\nSam's\nup your\nfather\nis\neight times as old as Sam. How\nold is each if seven years less\nthan the father's\nage\nis\none\nmore than six times Sam s age?\nJean Mears overheard\ntwo\nworkers in the plant talking\nabout their boss and this is what\none said: \"On the outside he is\nlowdown and mean. Underneath\nthough he is just the opposite,\nmean and lowdown.\u201d\nBernita Jennings says a cock\ntail party is where people drink\nthe Martini, eat the olive and\nspill the beans.\nA word to the wise is usual\nly sufficient and it is at this\ntime that we would like to\npass the word along that if\nyou are not registered to vote\nyou have until March 26 to\ndo so.\nIf you have\nmoved\nsince the last election or have\nnot voted in the last two elec\ntions you must correct\nyour\naddress in the first case and\nin the second you must go to\nthe Board of Elections and\nregister.\nThe workers failure to vote\nis the cause of many issues vital\nto their welfare being lost.\nDON'T BE LATE IN \u201858!\nRegister and VOTE!\neulating their petitions to get\nrid of YOUR UNION and then\nthey will get rid of you when\never\nthey please. Champion\nUnit members and their Un\nion have not given this com\np a n y any good reason for\nbreaking off good' relation\nship so why the petitions???\nThe reason is they will be\nable to take away all you\nhave gained In the past 17\nyears and give you a number\nas in the old days. Your fu\nture is as secure as you make\nit. DON\u2019T SIGN THE PE\nTITIONS!\nFISKE BROS. REFINING CO.\nMtmultichirfri of Fi\u00bbkr and Luhripinte\nGrraiti and All Typet of Lubricantt\n1500 Oakdale Ave.\nOX. 1-2491\nTOLEDO TOWEL\nSUPPLY COMPANY\nServing Toledo 48 Years\nComplete Industrial\nLinen Laundry Service\nalso CASH and CARRY\n322 E. Woodruff\nCH. 1-2297\nI\nTHE TOLEDO PORCELAIN\nENAMEL PRODUCTS CO.\nDivision of the Bettinger Corp.\nCOMPLETE ARCHITECTURAL\nPORCELAIN ENAMEL SERVICE\n2275 Smead Ave. CH. 4-9591 Toledo, Ohio\n\nNational Supply Unit News\nBy \u201cUNCLE REMUS\u201d\nHappenings around the shop: nate Unit officers and commit\nDoubt very much if the King teemen.\nMr. H. R. down there in Le\nFish supervisor in Weld shop\never sees the sunshine. He is noir City, Tenn., still waiting\nhere from 6:30 a.m. to 9 p.m. for that 1918 news.\nwnats me troubie. dont you\ntrust your T. U. college b0X5.\nMr. and Mrs. Orlo Worline\nare the proud parents of a baby\nboy. Orlo works in dept. 147.\nMr. Ray Schmidlin, dept. 153;\nwas grandfather for the first\nhe knew he\ntne\ntrouble.\ngrandfather\ntime He claims\nmake it before his wife,\nit out why Har\nwould\nCan t figure\nvev Sleep missed out on having\nhis picture taken. A good first\nvice president is always on the\nball.\nBoyce. night assembly\nboss, says his name is Olin not\nMr.\nOwen. Sorry for the error.\nThe only way the cafeteria is\nmoney on\ngoing to make any\nthe night shift is 4\npush cart again. If the help sees\nthe food, etc., they will buy.\nthe seniority\nto get that\nLooking over\nboard. Stanley\nBaranoski will\nwith Company\nhave 50 years\nwhen he is at retirement age ot\n65 Stanley, youse\nman.\nis a good\nMr. and Mrs. Harold Jones\ntheir 37th wed\nwill celebrate\nding anniversary March 24\nThe night maintenance boss.\nMr. B. K. has a new\nhobby. He\nwas operating a jack hammer\nlike a professional. Don t let the\nmethods dept, catch you if you\ndon t want a blood hound\nbreathing down your back.\nWho is the foreman in dept.\n143 with just seven men. who is\nso busy that it takes him\nuntil\nout checks. What\nnoon to pass\nwould he do with a full crew.\nWhile the Company is cutting\ndown on expenses we think it\nwould be a good time for them\nto get rid of some surplus fore\nmen. In our estimation some are\nentirely useless and it is im\nposition on the working men\nthe shop for them to carry sucn\npeople If hourly rated men are\nlaid off the foremen should be\nan im\nin\ncut down in proportion.\nSweet shades of Chanel No. 5.\nWhy is it that when some peo\nple get to be a foreman they\nevidently think that they should\nsmell like a girl? In dept. 143\nyou can t tell by the scent\na\nwhether it's\nwalking by.\nGannon or Lee\nWe wish to express our sym\npathy to the families of John\nBenson, W. Wright and Harry\nDoxsie.\nOn the sick list: Herb Gonger,\ndept 154. in Flower Hospital.\nBernard Bick, dept. 144. recup\nerating. Lemuel Childers, dept.\n750. in Flower Hospital.\nRegular Unit meeting Sun\nday, March 23. 10 a.m. in Par\nlor A at Local 12. Special order\nof business\u2014a nominating com-1\n_in tn nnmi-l\nmittee will be elected to nomi\n\u2019\u2022Red\u201d Wells\nFamous U. S. Prime\nCorn Fed Roast Beef\n2817 Monroe St\n1740 Sylvania Ave.\nI\n(greetings From\nAyling\nReichert\nBy MARY WYATT\nf\nI\nThe regular Credit Union\nmeeting was held on March 10\nat the home of H. Dunlap with\neight officers present. Follow\ning the business meeting, a\nluncheon was served by our\nhostess. Thanks to her for an\nThe next\nenjoyable evening.\nmeeting will be held at the\nhome of E. Ackley.\nCongratulations to G. Poland\non a grandson born March 12 to\ndaughter, Doretta, at Flower\nHospital.\n\nOn March 7. A&R lost an\nother employee due to retire\nment. Maudie Coker. our eighth\noldest employee in line of seni\nority decided to take life easy\nafter being with us since Dec. 6,\nShort: after beginning\n194s\nwork at A&R Maudie lost her\nhusband and so the task of raP.\ning a large family fell upon her\nshoulders. She was a steady and\nconscientious worker and not\nvery often did she not make an\nappearance on the job. The lit\ntle lady who was always seen\nand not heard will be missed by\nthe A&R gang.\nOn March 14 a farewell party\nwas given in her honor, at\nwhich time she was presented\nwith a nice maple rocker. At\nthis time we wish the best of\nluck to her in future days to\ncome and may God bless her\nwith a long and happy life.\nMaudie lives on Norwood\nAve., and celebrated her 66th\nbirthday on Sept. 19.\nA speedy recovery to Leola\nSherff in Room 348 at St.\nCharles Hospital.\nAlice and Karl Neipp attend;\ned the Cleveland Flower Show\nTo Buddy: It's action\nyou\nneed and not words at present.\nWe are glad to hear that Bob\nRigsby is recuperating nicely at\nhome since his recent heart at\ntack.\nThe only bad after effects\nthat Clarence Macklin has with\nhis pinched finger is that his\ndog takes the plastic finger\ncover for a bone.\nSEWER C1OGGED? M Your\nROTO-ROOTER\nService Man\nCH 4-4871\nFree Estimate*\nAll Sewer Jobs\nGuaranteed 2 Years\n23 Years Satisfied Service\n1713 DETROIT AVENUE\nCote Wrecking Co.\nW recking of Every Kind\nNew Used Materials For Sale\nUsed Lumber Plumbing Fixtures\nBonded Licensed Insured\n5870 Detroit Ave.\nGR. 2-5224\nA Serious Concern Of\n\nLabor-Management-Citizens\nAmerican money, contributed freely, has rebuilt many\nforeign industries which are now capturing the Jobs of\nAmerican workmen under trade policies which have pulled\nthis country's dykes apart.\nEmployes in the glass industry, important to Toledo as\nthe \"glass capital of the world,\" are not alone suffering.\nWorkers in textile, power machinery, plywood, tile, china,\nsteel wire, and chemicals, to name a few large segments of\nindustry, are being hard hit A substantial portion of the\n2,150 men currently idled in our Company is attributable to\nthe imports of glass from the low wage countries.\nCapitalism in Europe and Asia, where wages are one\nfifth to one-tenth what they are in America, is different from\ncapitalism in America where wage earners are industry's\nbest customers.\nik\n\u2018Dynamic capitalism of America has put a floor under\nwages by law, has restricted the import of foriegn laborers,\nhas distributed to our labor many of the benefits of tech\nnology and efficiency, has consciously increased purchasing\npower. This is the best answer to Communism to be found\nanywhere in the world. Now it is threatened because the\n\"labor ingredient\" of foreign-made goods costs so much less\nthan the same ingredient in competing American goods.\nIf we could extend the idea of American capitalism\nabroad so as to raise foreign wages rather than lower our\nown to world levels, we might be better able to compete\nfairly in our own primary markets and save American jobs.\nSurely such a plan is neither evil, nor greedy, nor contrary\nto the public weal.\nLIBBEY: OWENS FORD\naGkadCNameie GLASS\nC","height":"26892","width":"19632"}}
